ies of the 20th century – has had a profound influence on a wide array of fields, including classical philology, theology, the philosophy of the social sciences, literary theory, philosophy of law, critical social theory and the philosophy of art. This collection expands on some of these areas and takes his hermeneutics into yet new fields including narrative medicine, biotechnology, the politics of memory, the philosophy of place and the non-verbal language of the body. And, building on Gadamer’s well-known discussions with Heidegger, Habermas and Derrida, Inheriting Gadamer sets him in dialogue with Mahatma Gandhi, Christine Korsgaard, Charles Mills and others. In these ways, the volume holds fast to a Gadamerian virtue: cultivating our important philosophical traditions while embracing the constant need to re-think their meaning in new circumstances and in relation to new knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHermeneutics. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aAriail Reed, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCauchon, Steven Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFristedt, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalpas, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMannies, Whitney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClimans, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Lorenzo C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwayne Barthold, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVilhauer, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarnke, Georgia, econtributor.4ctb